{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Context\nAdd an `rebar.authorship.v1` attestation KIND on the foundation asymmetric\nattest substrate (`src/rebar/attest/`), so an event can be cryptographically\nsigned by an author identity and verified against that identity's in-band public\nkeys. This is the signing/verifying MACHINERY (registration + sign/verify + trust\nroot); WIRING it into the write path and enforcement is a later leaf (3183). Builds\non ddbe (identity entity holds `keys`) and the foundation SSHSIG scheme.\n\n## Why\nAuthorship certification needs a tamper-evident proof that a specific identity\nauthored an event, verifiable offline against public keys carried in-band on the\nidentity entity (no external PKI). Reusing the foundation `attest` substrate gives\npolicy-pinned scheme selection (closes the alg-confusion class) for free.\n\n## What\n### 1. New module `src/rebar/attest/authorship.py`\nConstants: `AUTHORSHIP_KIND = \"rebar.authorship.v1\"`,\n`AUTHORSHIP_NAMESPACE = \"rebar.authorship.v1\"`,\n`PAYLOAD_TYPE = \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\"`.\n\n- `register_authorship_policy() -> None` (idempotent): pins\n  `registry.POLICY[AUTHORSHIP_KIND] = registry.Policy(scheme=\"sshsig\",\n  namespace=AUTHORSHIP_NAMESPACE)`. (The `sshsig` SCHEME is already registered by\n  `sshsig.register_sshsig_scheme()`; this pins the KIND→scheme policy so\n  `registry.verify` selects the scheme from source-pinned policy, never from the\n  envelope.) Wire the call into `src/rebar/attest/__init__.py` right after the\n  existing `sshsig.register_sshsig_scheme()` line, so it is live at import.\n- `sign_authorship(payload: bytes, key_path: str, principal: str) -> dsse.Envelope`:\n  FIRST call `sshsig.ensure_available()` (raises `sshsig.SshKeygenUnavailable`\n  when ssh-keygen is missing/too old — the honest precondition; without this\n  `sshsig.sign`'s `subprocess.run(check=True)` would instead raise\n  `FileNotFoundError`/`CalledProcessError`). Then `pae = dsse.pae(PAYLOAD_TYPE, payload)`; `sig = sshsig.sign(pae, key_path,\n  AUTHORSHIP_NAMESPACE)`; return `dsse.Envelope(PAYLOAD_TYPE, payload,\n  [dsse.Signature(keyid=principal, sig=sig)])`. `principal` is the author identity's\n  id (it becomes the SSHSIG `-I` principal — `SshsigScheme.verify` reads\n  `signatures[0].keyid` as the principal). Raises `sshsig.SshKeygenUnavailable` if\n  ssh-keygen is missing/too old (do not swallow — signing must be honest).\n- `allowed_signers_from_keys(keys: list[str], principal: str) -> str`: build SSHSIG\n  allowed_signers content — one line per key, `\"<principal> <authorized-keys-line>\"`\n  (the identity's `keys` are OpenSSH authorized-keys lines like\n  `\"ssh-ed25519 AAAA...\"`; prefixing the principal yields a valid allowed_signers\n  entry). Join with `\"\\n\"`. Skip blank/malformed key entries.\n- `resolve_trust_root(identity_id: str, *, repo_root=None) -> str | None`: load the\n  identity via `rebar.show_ticket(identity_id, repo_root=...)`; if it is an\n  `identity` ticket with a non-empty `keys` list, return\n  `allowed_signers_from_keys(keys, principal=identity_id)`; else `None` (unknown\n  identity or no keys → nothing to trust).\n- `verify_authorship(envelope: dsse.Envelope, identity_id: str, *, repo_root=None)\n  -> registry.Verdict`: `trust_root = resolve_trust_root(identity_id, ...)`; if\n  `None`, return a non-verified `registry.Verdict(False, \"unknown_principal\",\n  reason=...)`; else return `registry.verify(AUTHORSHIP_KIND, envelope,\n  trust_root)`. The envelope's signature `keyid` MUST equal `identity_id` (the\n  principal) or SSHSIG verification fails — this is what makes \"signed by A does not\n  verify against B\" hold: verifying A's envelope against B builds B's allowed_signers\n  (B's keys, principal=B_id), and neither the key nor the principal matches.\n\n### 2. Determinism / trust-root selection\nTrust root is ALWAYS resolved from the identity entity's in-band `keys` (never from\nthe envelope), and the scheme is ALWAYS selected from source-pinned\n`POLICY[AUTHORSHIP_KIND]`. A caller cannot smuggle a scheme or a trust anchor\nthrough the envelope.\n\n## Scope\nIn: the authorship module (constants, policy registration, sign, verify, trust-root\nresolution, allowed_signers builder) and its registration in `attest/__init__.py`.\nOut: signing real events at the write seam / storing the envelope on events\n(3183 enforcement), key lifecycle & rotation (e165). `payload` here is arbitrary\nbytes supplied by the caller (later the event's canonical bytes); bde5 does not\ndecide what bytes an event contributes.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `register_authorship_policy()` pins `POLICY[\"rebar.authorship.v1\"]` to\n  `Policy(scheme=\"sshsig\", namespace=\"rebar.authorship.v1\")` and is invoked at\n  `attest` package import; a test asserts `registry.resolve(\"rebar.authorship.v1\")`\n  returns that policy.\n- [ ] Round-trip: given an ssh keypair whose PUBLIC key is stored on identity A's\n  `keys`, `sign_authorship(payload, privkey, principal=A_id)` produces an envelope\n  that `verify_authorship(envelope, A_id)` reports `verified=True`\n  (test skips if `ssh-keygen` unavailable via `sshsig.ensure_available`).\n- [ ] Cross-identity rejection: the SAME envelope verified against a DIFFERENT\n  identity B (different keypair) reports `verified=False` (B's in-band keys are the\n  trust root, and neither key nor principal matches).\n- [ ] Tamper rejection: mutating the envelope `payload` (or a signature byte) makes\n  `verify_authorship(..., A_id)` report `verified=False`.\n- [ ] Unknown/keyless identity: `verify_authorship` against an id that is not an\n  `identity` ticket, or one with empty `keys`, returns a non-verified Verdict\n  (never raises).\n\n## file_impact\n- `src/rebar/attest/authorship.py` (new: constants, register_authorship_policy, sign_authorship, allowed_signers_from_keys, resolve_trust_root, verify_authorship)\n- `src/rebar/attest/__init__.py` (call register_authorship_policy() at import, after sshsig registration)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783832327739345001,"uuid":"25756119-f98e-4156-b67b-1c7f15ab79c7"}